\subsection{Gene Regulatory Networks}\label{gene-regulatory-networks}

Gene regulatory network are complex networks of interactions between
genes, transcription factors, and other molecules that control gene
expression.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Nodes and Edges}: Nodes represent genes/regulatory elements;
  edges represent interactions, such as activation or
  represion.\hspace{0pt}
\item
  \textbf{Transcription Factors}: Bind to specific DNA sequences to
  regulate gene transcription. Regulate the transcription of target
  genes, turning them on or off. \hspace{0pt}
\item
  \textbf{Feedback Loops}: Create regulatory dynamics through
  self-influence. Can be positive or negative \hspace{0pt}
\item
  \textbf{Signal Integration}: Combines multiple signals from different
  pathways. Coordinates gene expression in response to stimuli.
  \hspace{0pt}
\end{itemize}

There are 3 types of regulation:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Simple regulation}: transcription factor Y is activated by a
  signal, when active it binds to X to enhance its transcription rate
  \hspace{0pt}
\item
  \textbf{Positive Autoregulation}: X is a transcription factor that
  activates itself, \hspace{0pt}
\item
  \textbf{Negative Autoregulation}: X is a transcription factor that
  represses itself \hspace{0pt}
\end{itemize}
